Let r, s be numbers and \mathbf {A}, \mathbf {B} be appropriately sized matrices. Then the following hold:

r(s\mathbf {A})=(rs)\mathbf {A}

(r+s)\mathbf {A}=r\mathbf {A}+s\mathbf {A} (distributivity)

r(\mathbf {A}+\mathbf {B})=r\mathbf {A}+r\mathbf {B}

Let \mathbf {A} be an n\times  n square matrix. We can introduce two matrices
\mathbf {A}_{\text {ant}}=\frac {\mathbf {A}-\mathbf {A}^{\mathsf {T}}}{2}
which is the "antisymmetric part" of \mathbf {A}, and
\mathbf {A}_{\text {sym}}=\frac {\mathbf {A}+\mathbf {A}^{\mathsf {T}}}{2}
which is the "symmetric part" of \mathbf {A}. Prove or find a counter-example:
\mathbf {A} = \mathbf {A}_{\text {ant}}+\mathbf {A}_{\text {sym}}.

Now, we can start calculating the first components, leaving the entries yet to be calculated as question marks:
\begin {align*}
\mathbf {A}\mathbf {B} &= \begin {bmatrix}\color {red}3 & \color {red}1 & \color {red}6\\2 & 1 & 3
\end {bmatrix}\begin {bmatrix}
\color {red} 2 & 1 & 7\\
\color {red} 6 & 1 & 0\\
\color {red} 1 & -1 & 5
\end {bmatrix}\\
&=\begin {bmatrix}3\cdot 2+1\cdot 6+6\cdot 1 & ? & ?\\
? & ? & ?\end {bmatrix}\\
&=\begin {bmatrix}18 & ? & ?\\
? & ? & ?\end {bmatrix}
\end {align*}

Observe
\begin {bmatrix}1 & 1\\0 & 1\end {bmatrix}
\begin {bmatrix}1 & 0\\1 & 1\end {bmatrix}
= \begin {bmatrix}2 & 1\\1 & 1\end {bmatrix}.
But
\begin {bmatrix}1 & 0\\1 & 1\end {bmatrix}
\begin {bmatrix}1 & 1\\0 & 1\end {bmatrix}
= \begin {bmatrix}1 & 1\\1 & 2\end {bmatrix}.
Since these are different matrices, we see that matrix multiplication is noncommutative (unlike multiplying real numbers).

So we can write a system of m equations in n unknowns using an m\times  n matrix \mathbf {A} and a n-vector \vec {b} as
\mathbf {A}\vec {x} = \vec {b}.
We can solve it by multiplying both sides by the left inverse of \mathbf {A}. When m=n, the left-hand side becomes:
\begin {align*}
\mathbf {A}^{-1}(\mathbf {A}\vec {x})&=(\mathbf {A}^{-1}\mathbf {A})\vec {x}\\
&=\mathbf {I}_{n}\vec {x}\\
&=\vec {x}
\end {align*}
The right-hand side becomes \mathbf {A}^{-1}\vec {b}. So we find the solution:
\vec {x} = \mathbf {A}^{-1}\vec {b}.

We can create a system of equations by introducing two unknowns p_{w} for the price of 1 quarter of wheat, and p_{i} for the price of 1 ton of iron. We assume society is in a "self reproducing state", in the sense that the wheat sector exchanges enough wheat-for-iron to continue producing wheat (and the iron sector exchanges enough iron-for-wheat to continue producing iron):
\begin {array}{rcl}
    280p_{w} + 12p_{i} &=& 400p_{w}\\
    120p_{w} + 8p_{i} &=& 20p_{i}.
\end {array}
We can rewrite the first equation (by subtracting both sides by 280p_{w}):
\begin {array}{rcl}
    12p_{i} &=& 120p_{w}\\
    120p_{w} + 8p_{i} &=& 20p_{i}.
\end {array}
Then we rewrite the second equation (by subtracting both sides by 8p_{i}):
\begin {array}{rcl}
    12p_{i} &=& 120p_{w}\\
    120p_{w} &=& 12p_{i}.
\end {array}
These are redundant equations! We end up with a class of solutions, described by
\boxed {10p_{w} = p_{i},}
that is to say, the price of 1 ton iron is equal to the price of 10 quarters of wheat.

More generally, a System of m Linear Equations in n Unknowns  x_{1}, …, x_{n} (where the subscripts are Indices to append to one symbol x a number or "dummy variable" [a variable ranging over the index values], giving us any number of variables for the price of one symbol) looks like:
\begin {array}{rcl}
a_{1,1}x_{1} + a_{1,2}x_{2} + … + a_{1,n}x_{n} &=& b_{1}\\
a_{2,1}x_{1} + a_{2,2}x_{2} + … + a_{2,n}x_{n} &=& b_{2}\\
\vdots \quad  \qquad \vdots \quad \qquad \ddots \quad \qquad \vdots \quad  & \vdots  & \vdots \\
a_{m,1}x_{1} + a_{m,2}x_{2} + … + a_{m,n}x_{n} &=& b_{m}
\end {array}
where b_{1}, …, b_{m} are m real constants, and we have a_{1,1}, a_{1,2}, …, a_{m,n} be mn real constants called the Coefficients.

One method to find a solution, which has been taught to high school students for decades, is to take the first equation and use it to rewrite one variable in terms of the remaining. For example, in:
\begin {array}{rcrcrcl}
    0      & + & 2x_{2} & + & 3x_{3} & = & 5\\
    2x_{1} & + & 0      & + & 3x_{3} &=& -1\\
    x_{1}  & + & x_{2}  & + & x_{3} &=& 1.
  \end {array}
We would use the first equation to substitute x_{2}=(5 - 3x_{3})/2 in the remaining equations, and discard the first equation, giving us:
\begin {array}{rcrcrcl}
    2x_{1} & + & 0      & + & 3x_{3} &=& -1\\
    x_{1}  & + & \displaystyle \left (\frac {5 - 3x_{3}}{2}\right )  & + & x_{3} &=& 1.
  \end {array}
We do this again, to use the first equation to write x_{1} = (-1-3x_{3})/2, and plug this into the last equation, which gives us a value for x_{3}.

Let m, n be positive integers. We define an m-by-n Matrix \mathbf {A} to be a rectangular array of mn real [or complex] numbers arranged in m horizontal Rows and n vertical Columns, written:
\mathbf {A}
= \left (\begin {array}{cccccc}
  a_{11} & a_{12} & … & a_{1j} & … & a_{1n} \\
a_{21} & a_{22} & … & a_{2j} & … & a_{2n}  \\
\vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  \\
a_{i1} & a_{i2} & … & a_{ij} & … & a_{in} \\
\vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  \\
a_{m1} & a_{m2} & …   & a_{mj} & …  & a_{mn} 
\end {array}\right )
\begin {array}{c}
  \\
  \gets  i^{\text {th}}\hbox {\ row}
\end {array}
We have highlighted the i^{\text {th}} row, and the j^{\text {th}} column.

We call an m\times  n matrix \mathbf {A}=(a_{i,j}) Upper Triangular if a_{i,j}=0 for i>j, e.g., when m=n it looks like: \mathbf {A} = \begin {bmatrix}
    a_{1,1} & a_{1,2} & a_{1,3} & … & a_{1,n}\\
    0      & a_{2,2} & a_{2,3} & … & a_{2,n}\\
    0      & 0       & a_{3,3} & … & a_{3,n}\\
    \vdots  & \vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots \\
    0      & 0      & 0      & …  & a_{n,n}
  \end {bmatrix}

We call an m\times  n matrix \mathbf {A}=(a_{i,j}) Lower Triangular if a_{i,j}=0 for i<j, e.g., when m=n it looks like: \mathbf {A} = \begin {bmatrix}
    a_{1,1} & 0      & 0       & … & 0\\
    a_{2,1} & a_{2,2} & 0       & … & 0\\
    a_{3,1} & a_{3,2} & a_{3,3} & … & 0\\
    \vdots  & \vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots \\
    a_{n,1} & a_{n,2} & a_{n,3} & …  & a_{n,n}
  \end {bmatrix}

It is useful to draw horizontal and vertical lines (either dashed or slid, it makes no difference except for typography), to partition a matrix into blocks, permitting us to write
\mathbf {A} = \left [
    \begin {array}{c:c}
        \mathbf {B} & \mathbf {C} \\ \hdashline 
        \mathbf {D} & \mathbf {E} 
    \end {array}
\right ] = \left [
    \begin {array}{c|c}
        \mathbf {B} & \mathbf {C} \\ \hline 
        \mathbf {D} & \mathbf {E} 
    \end {array}
\right ].
We could partition a matrix however we want, and we call the blocks Submatrices of \mathbf {A}. Writing \mathbf {A} in this manner is called a Block Decomposition of \mathbf {A}.

Let r, s be numbers and \mathbf {A}, \mathbf {B} be appropriately sized matrices. Then the following hold:

r(s\mathbf {A})=(rs)\mathbf {A}

(r+s)\mathbf {A}=r\mathbf {A}+s\mathbf {A} (distributivity)

r(\mathbf {A}+\mathbf {B})=r\mathbf {A}+r\mathbf {B}

Let \mathbf {A} be an n\times  n square matrix. We can introduce two matrices
\mathbf {A}_{\text {ant}}=\frac {\mathbf {A}-\mathbf {A}^{\mathsf {T}}}{2}
which is the "antisymmetric part" of \mathbf {A}, and
\mathbf {A}_{\text {sym}}=\frac {\mathbf {A}+\mathbf {A}^{\mathsf {T}}}{2}
which is the "symmetric part" of \mathbf {A}. Prove or find a counter-example:
\mathbf {A} = \mathbf {A}_{\text {ant}}+\mathbf {A}_{\text {sym}}.

Now, we can start calculating the first components, leaving the entries yet to be calculated as question marks:
\begin {align*}
\mathbf {A}\mathbf {B} &= \begin {bmatrix}\color {red}3 & \color {red}1 & \color {red}6\\2 & 1 & 3
\end {bmatrix}\begin {bmatrix}
\color {red} 2 & 1 & 7\\
\color {red} 6 & 1 & 0\\
\color {red} 1 & -1 & 5
\end {bmatrix}\\
&=\begin {bmatrix}3\cdot 2+1\cdot 6+6\cdot 1 & ? & ?\\
? & ? & ?\end {bmatrix}\\
&=\begin {bmatrix}18 & ? & ?\\
? & ? & ?\end {bmatrix}
\end {align*}

Observe
\begin {bmatrix}1 & 1\\0 & 1\end {bmatrix}
\begin {bmatrix}1 & 0\\1 & 1\end {bmatrix}
= \begin {bmatrix}2 & 1\\1 & 1\end {bmatrix}.
But
\begin {bmatrix}1 & 0\\1 & 1\end {bmatrix}
\begin {bmatrix}1 & 1\\0 & 1\end {bmatrix}
= \begin {bmatrix}1 & 1\\1 & 2\end {bmatrix}.
Since these are different matrices, we see that matrix multiplication is noncommutative (unlike multiplying real numbers).

So we can write a system of m equations in n unknowns using an m\times  n matrix \mathbf {A} and a n-vector \vec {b} as
\mathbf {A}\vec {x} = \vec {b}.
We can solve it by multiplying both sides by the left inverse of \mathbf {A}. When m=n, the left-hand side becomes:
\begin {align*}
\mathbf {A}^{-1}(\mathbf {A}\vec {x})&=(\mathbf {A}^{-1}\mathbf {A})\vec {x}\\
&=\mathbf {I}_{n}\vec {x}\\
&=\vec {x}
\end {align*}
The right-hand side becomes \mathbf {A}^{-1}\vec {b}. So we find the solution:
\vec {x} = \mathbf {A}^{-1}\vec {b}.

If we look at a parallelogram in the real plane, then we can describe two edges using vectors \vec {v}=(x_{1},y_{1}) and \vec {w}=(x_{2},y_{2}). Its area is precisely:
A = \det \begin {pmatrix}x_{1} & x_{2}\\y_{1} & y_{2}\end {pmatrix}
This is taught to students in calculus. Similarly, if we extend our discussion to a parallelipid in three dimensions, we would have three vectors and the volume would be the determinant of the matrix whose columns are these column vectors.

